results.notes: A terrific edible. This becomes very prolific in my very specific location in July-Sept for some reason. It doesnt appear to be this way everywhere in AB. Young-middle aged Trembling Aspen monoculture (wild rose, wild strawberry, saskatoon and some other small shrubs present). It occurs alongside Leccinum, rarely Boletus Edulis, cortinarius sp., russulae sp., chaciporus piperatus, A. Muscaria var guessowii. The older specimens are insect infected quickly, but the young ones are typically good. The insects infect from the base upward, the stipe changes from yellow to red exterior and you can almost cut it along that color line to determine how high the insects have gotten. They are quick growing and nearly daily in one patch of forest maybe 10×20m you go pick the choice young specimens and fill a couple ice cream pails full. The same the next day and if the rains continue you can do this roughly for a month getting both Leccinum and Hemi in quantities enough to be a staple dehydrated food over the winter.

results.notes: Found 2 wet yrs in a row in same location under young trembling aspen monoculture. No spruce or other trees present. It is different than 2 other observations i have made on boletus in Northern AB in that no spruce are present. My first thought to sub species was Chippewanesis but i really have no idea. I am very curious as to what subspecies we have here. It was present alongside ample Hemileccinum and leccinum as well as Chalciporus piperatus, various cortinarius sp, russula sp, and A. muscaria. I think the Amanita and boletus as well as piperatus seem to have an affinity…just a hunch.

results.notes:

Macro: Thallus continuous-areolate, areoles separated by distinct cracks. Areoles mostly convex. Surface light blue-gray, underlain by brown where specimen has rubbed against packet or something else. Apothecia up to ~0.5 mm, uncommon, black, with some having crusty white-gray pruina.

Micro: hymenium plus epi ~125 micrometers tall, epihymenium greenish brown with a hint of aeruginose pigment when freshly mounted. Paraphyses submoniliform with apical cells globose to subglobose or ellipsoid, lower cells generally ellipsoid.

Chemistry: K- thallus, hymenium I+blueish quickly becoming reddish yellow and eventually turning deep red (exciple stays yellowish)
